issue.title: Mispronunciation with Kokoro models
issue.body:
Hello, I apologize if this issue is out of scope. I have been noticing that this implementation of Kokoro seems to mispronounce words at a much greater rate compared to reference implementations. Consider this prompt, using the `af_alloy` voice.

`Imagine a great demon obscured by a dusky cloak that fluttered in the breeze.`

This is the result from TTS.cpp:

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a2f21e3c-cef8-445a-a1ad-d6dc0cc17a02

Meanwhile, this is the result from the [Kokoro HF space](https://huggingface.co/spaces/hexgrad/Kokoro-TTS):

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/77cbb705-6133-4a32-9102-9325c97573d0

Any idea how I can improve the output pronunciation ?

pull_request.title: refactor: convert App folder from Flow to TypeScript
pull_request.body:
# refactor: convert App folder from Flow to TypeScript ## Summary This PR converts the `src/components/App` folder from Flow to TypeScript as part of the ongoing migration effort in the `eh/feat/DHIS2-19350-refactor-flow-to-typescript` branch. **Files converted:** - `App.component.js` `App.component.tsx` - Main App component with Redux Provider setup - `AppContents.component.js` `AppContents.component.tsx` - App container with Material-UI styling - `index.js` `index.ts` - Simple export barrel **Key changes:** - Removed Flow syntax (`// @flow`, exact object types `{| ... |}`) - Added TypeScript type definitions following project patterns - Applied Material-UI `withStyles` TypeScript pattern with `WithStyles` - Fixed import ordering to satisfy ESLint requirements - Used `any` type for Redux store prop (see notes below) ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **Start the app locally** (`yarn start`) and verify it renders without errors - most critical test - [ ] **Evaluate store typing approach**: I used `any` for the Redux store prop instead of the proper `ReduxStore` type due to a TypeScript error. Consider if this is acceptable or if the typing should be fixed properly. - [ ] **Verify Material-UI styling**: Check that the app container styling still works correctly after the TypeScript conversion **Recommended test plan:** 1. Run `yarn start` and access http://localhost:3000 2. Verify the app loads without console errors 3. Check that basic navigation and rendering works as expected --- ### Diagram ```mermaid %%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%% graph TD App["src/components/App/
App.component.tsx"]:::major-edit AppContents["src/components/App/
AppContents.component.tsx"]:::major-edit Index["src/components/App/
index.ts"]:::major-edit Provider["react-redux
Provider"]:::context MaterialUI["@material-ui/core
withStyles"]:::context ReduxStore["capture-core-utils/
types/global.ts
(ReduxStore)"]:::context App --> Provider App --> AppContents AppContents --> MaterialUI App -.-> ReduxStore Index --> App subgraph Legend L1[Major Edit]:::major-edit L2[Minor Edit]:::minor-edit L3[Context/No Edit]:::context end classDef major-edit fill:#90EE90 classDef minor-edit fill:#87CEEB classDef context fill:#FFFFFF ``` ### Notes - **Type safety trade-off**: Used `any` for Redux store type instead of `ReduxStore` due to Provider compatibility issues. This reduces type safety but maintains the minimal conversion approach specified in the migration guidelines. - **Pre-existing issues**: There are unrelated TypeScript errors in `TeiSearch.component.tsx` and i18n scanner warnings that existed before this conversion. - **Linting compliance**: Import order was adjusted to satisfy ESLint rules (absolute imports before relative imports). **Link to Devin run**: https://app.devin.ai/sessions/03941795b1214a7b8d2f3ccd4d41307f **Requested by**: henrik.vadet@dhis2.org

commits.message:
Fix measurement timing root cause: corrected variant selectors and positioning

- Fixed ensureVariantsAtZeroPosition to use correct selector data-figma-type=COMPONENT instead of data-figma-variant-id
- Added important CSS properties to override conflicting styles during positioning
- Enhanced measureVariantPositions with requestAnimationFrame timing and position verification
- Added forced repositioning fallback when variants are not at same position
- Enhanced debugging and logging for positioning verification
- Fixed component set selector in performVariantSwitchWithCorrectMeasurement
- Added processElementsForAnimation to skip variant-level elements in animation

Core issue: Measurements were happening before positioning changes were applied,
and wrong selectors meant variants were not being positioned at all.
This eliminates false positive position differences in variant containers.

Changelog

Sourced from react-router's changelog.

7.8.0

Minor Changes

  • Add nonce prop to Links & PrefetchPageLinks (#14048)
  • Add loaderData arguments/properties alongside existing data arguments/properties to provide consistency and clarity between loaderData and actionData across the board (#14047)
    • Updated types: Route.MetaArgs, Route.MetaMatch, MetaArgs, MetaMatch, Route.ComponentProps.matches, UIMatch
    • @deprecated warnings have been added to the existing data properties to point users to new loaderData properties, in preparation for removing the data properties in a future major release

Patch Changes

  • Prevent "Did not find corresponding fetcher result" console error when navigating during a fetcher.submit revalidation (#14114)

  • Bubble client-side middleware errors prior to next to the appropriate ancestor error boundary (#14138)

  • Switch Lazy Route Discovery manifest URL generation to usea standalone URLSearchParams instance instead of URL.searchParams to avoid a major performance bottleneck in Chrome (#14084)

  • Adjust internal RSC usage of React.use to avoid Webpack compilation errors when using React 18 (#14113)

  • Remove dependency on @types/node in TypeScript declaration files (#14059)

  • Fix types for UIMatch to reflect that the loaderData/data properties may be undefined (#12206)

    • When an ErrorBoundary is being rendered, not all active matches will have loader data available, since it may have been their loader that threw to trigger the boundary
    • The UIMatch.data type was not correctly handing this and would always reflect the presence of data, leading to the unexpected runtime errors when an ErrorBoundary was rendered
    • This may cause some type errors to show up in your code for unguarded match.data accesses - you should properly guard for undefined values in those scenarios.
    // app/root.tsx
export function loader() {
  someFunctionThatThrows(); //  Throws an Error
  return { title: "My Title" };
}

    export function Layout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
let matches = useMatches();
let rootMatch = matches[0] as UIMatch<Awaited<ReturnType<typeof loader>>>;
//  ^ rootMatch.data is incorrectly typed here, so TypeScript does not
//    complain if you do the following which throws an error at runtime:
let { title } = rootMatch.data; // 
    

    return <html>...</html>;
}

  • [UNSTABLE] Ensure resource route errors go through handleError w/middleware enabled (#14078)

  • [UNSTABLE] Propagate returned Response from server middleware if next wasn't called (#14093)

  • [UNSTABLE] Allow server middlewares to return data() values which will be converted into a Response (#14093)

... (truncated)

issue.body: [Issue #10241](https://github.com/elastic/security-team/issues/10241) **Motivation** When users opt for a manual deployment today, they have the option to deploy an agent on macOS, Windows, RPM, and DEB. However, Cloudbeat only supports Linux and Kubernetes. While its true that the same agent policy may include other integrations supporting these operating systems, it doesnt make sense to propose these options after our integration installation. The goal of this ticket is to update the warning text to be much more explicit about our inability to work on those options. **Definition of done** - [ ] Update the warning text to be much more explicit about our inability to work on those options.
